The measurements were conducted at the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research (JINR) in Dubna, specifically in the Cyclotron Laboratory (CYCLONE), using a proton energy of 1 GeV. The experiment aimed to investigate the production of mesons resulting from the interaction of relativistic protons with HM Ta (reaction, π+). The experimental setup included two scintillation detectors, S1 and S2, for registering particles emitted into the forward hemisphere, and three scintillation detectors, S3-S5, for measuring the angular distribution of particles produced in the interactions under study. The obtained data were compared with the AJ model developed based on response.

Introduction
Meson production is one of the most significant phenomena in hadronic interactions and plays a crucial role in fields such as astrophysics, cosmic ray physics, and accelerator technology. Here, we present differential data on meson production in the federal collisions of relativistic protons with Ta (reaction, π+). These experiments were conducted at the CYCLONE laboratory in JINR-Dubna.

Experimental Setup
The experimental setup used in our experiment includes:
- Two scintillation detectors, S1 and S2;
- Three scintillation detectors;
- An improved collimator;
- A target made of 0.1 mm thick tantalum foil;
- A detection system consisting of four scintillation detectors, T1-T4.

